{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/pilonidal-sinus-disease/background-information/pathophysiology/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"70e5ecd9-dcfe-5b6a-a5d1-3e251a673bd4","slug":"pathophysiology","fullItemName":"Pathophysiology","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 126336d1-7d36-4ef4-94f6-97cbc5c5c7ce --><h2>How does pilonidal sinus disease develop?</h2><!-- end field 126336d1-7d36-4ef4-94f6-97cbc5c5c7ce -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item e18cfe36-686f-497c-a38a-5e6f78689113 --><!-- begin field b147a630-1efe-46e9-9513-0a9a7a5a415d --><ul><li><strong>Opinions differ as to how pilonidal sinus disease develops.</strong> It was initially thought to be a congenital condition, but the current consensus is that it is an acquired condition caused by loose hairs in the natal cleft [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/pilonidal-sinus-disease/references/\">BMJ, 2018</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/pilonidal-sinus-disease/references/\">Kober, 2018</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/pilonidal-sinus-disease/references/\">Kuckelman, 2018</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/pilonidal-sinus-disease/references/\">Iesalnieks, 2019</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/pilonidal-sinus-disease/references/\">Johnson, 2019</a>]:<ul><li>The hairs are driven into the skin of the natal cleft by a rolling action of the buttocks. This causes a foreign body reaction in surrounding tissue, leading to the formation of a pit (a fistulous opening) in the midline of the natal cleft.</li><li>The pit fills with dead skin and other debris, which are driven into the depth of the pit. This promotes a chronic inflammatory reaction, resulting in the formation of a sinus (an abnormal epithelialized connection with the skin surface).</li><li>Over time, further debris are forced into the midline pit and build up under pressure to create an underlying cavity or track, which communicates with the overlying skin through the sinus.</li><li>An abscess may form (due to moist conditions in the natal cleft that favour bacterial proliferation) and may discharge into a sinus, or become larger over time.</li><li>A sinus may have one or more secondary openings lateral to the primary pit, and if open, these may chronically discharge pus or blood.</li></ul></li><li>Although the significance of cleft hair in the development of pilonidal disease is widely accepted, it is unclear whether the development of the disease is secondary to local pressure on the tissues, ruptured hair follicles, hypoxic tissue beds, or a congenital vulnerability of the natal skin [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/pilonidal-sinus-disease/references/\">Johnson, 2019</a>].</li><li>Alternative pathophysiological theories not relating to stray-hair insertion do not adequately explain the few reported cases of pilonidal sinus disease involving other parts of the body, such as on the scalp, axilla, groin, or in between the fingers of barbers, hairdressers, and dog groomers [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/pilonidal-sinus-disease/references/\">BMJ, 2018</a>].</li></ul><!-- end field b147a630-1efe-46e9-9513-0a9a7a5a415d --><!-- end item e18cfe36-686f-497c-a38a-5e6f78689113 -->","topic":{"id":"c75a0f03-60df-5718-b4ad-d6e32f354f69","topicId":"f6f74445-1669-4cf9-9d42-9881d6be83d1","topicName":"Pilonidal sinus disease","slug":"pilonidal-sinus-disease","lastRevised":"Last revised in March 2019","chapters":[{"id":"685753f4-4b6f-54e1-b69e-fafd200dee31","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"5f89fe48-e69a-565c-9208-1e39eafec872","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","subChapters":[]},{"id":"e102b